 relationship between the state and local actors created another contested facet of modern Yunnan's transformation. Competing narratives emerged when local actors negotiated and reconstructed their status within the contemporary Chinese nation-state. Bandits became heroes; separatists became patriots; a vibrant regional center became an isolated, exotic, and marginal province of the People's Republic of China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBorderlandszIndus River RegionxHistory. 0aBorderlandszMekong River RegionyHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aHistory. 4aModern History. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aYunnan, borderlands, frontier, Southeast Asia, China.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311133235240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048559008?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048559008zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048559008/original  a978-3-11-133235-2 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA